<main class="content-container">
    <p style=" margin-bottom: 1rem; font-size: 20px;">Soy wax is a vegetable wax made from the oil of soybeans.
        After harvesting,
        the beans are cleaned, cracked, de-hulled, and rolled into flakes. The oil is then extracted from the
        flakes and hydrogenated.

        The hydrogenation process converts some of the fatty acids in the oil from unsaturated to saturated.
        This process dramatically alters the melting point of the oil, making it solid at room temperature. The
        leftover bean husks are commonly used as animal feed.

        The U.S. grows the vast majority of the world's soybeans, primarily in Illinois, Iowa, and Indiana.</p>

